{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488315"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:36:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:36:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"410"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/410"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.45,0.08,0.08,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108957"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/410"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91327"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"904"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2648"},{"type":"tags","id":"3813"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9121"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40419"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108957"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department by ambulance from home with a two-day history of vomiting, colicky abdominal pain, distension and absolute constipation. This is on a background of increasing constipation over the last three months. She has a medical history of congestive cardiac failure (LV ejection fraction 25%) and COPD. Her medications include metoprolol, ramipril, frusemide and a regular ICS/LAMA/LABA inhaler. She has a 40 pack-year smoking history. She reports becoming short of breath after walking short distances. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her abdomen is distended and tympanic with high-pitched bowel sounds. There is tenderness in the left iliac fossa. Her rectum is empty. She is admitted under the surgical team and a CT scan shows a stenosing lesion in the sigmoid colon and ascites.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hartmann\u0027s procedure","Colonic stent","Therapeutic paracentesis","Transverse colostomy","Defunctioning loop ileostomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient displays symptoms and signs consistent with a large bowel obstruction. Based on her history of constipation, as well as the CT scan, which demonstrates a stenosing lesion in the sigmoid colon, this bowel obstruction is likely secondary to a neoplasm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIdeally a patient with a stenosing colorectal cancer would be offered a primary resection. In situations like this, where the patient has an acute bowel obstruction, an emergency \u003Cstrong\u003EHartmann\u0027s procedure\u003C/strong\u003E might be appropriate. In this case however, the patient is not a good surgical candidate due to her comorbid state. The ascites is also suggestive of metastatic spread, another factor that weighs against a surgical option. For these reasons, Hartmann\u0027s procedure, \u003Cstrong\u003Etransverse colostomy\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edefunctioning loop ileostomy\u003C/strong\u003E are not the best answer options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Etherapeutic paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E might be of benefit, this patient requires some sort of intervention to relieve her bowel obstruction in the acute setting. As such, therapeutic paracentesis is not indicated as a priority at this point in time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven all of the factors outlined above, the preferred method of bowel decompression in this case would be to place a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonic stent.\u003C/strong\u003E The indications for stents include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBridge to surgery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDecompression for inoperable/unresectable disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPalliative management\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of the unfit patient\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndoscopic stenting is as effective as surgical intervention in the management of obstructing bowel cancer, but is associated with significantly shorter recovery times and fewer complications. The latter point is important for this patient, as major bowel surgery would carry a high degree of risk, both from a surgical and anaesthetic standpoint.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colonic stenting offers good palliation for patients with inoperable, obstructing bowel cancers."],"references":["Malakorn S, Stein SL, Lee JH, You YN. Urgent Management of Obstructing Colorectal Cancer: Divert, Stent, or Resect? J Gastrointest Surg. 2019;23(2):425-432. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30284201/","Ma B, Ren T, Cai C, et al. Palliative procedures for advanced obstructive colorectal cancer:\na systematic review and meta\u2011analysis. Int J Colorectal Dis. 2024; 39:148-61."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91327"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"410"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91327"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-15T10:34:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-15T10:35:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"410"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108957"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/385"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Colorectal cancer","synon